description:
A dead bird, looks to be an American Coot. I found it next to a stream and lake, and on top of a crushed soda can. Its neck was twisted to the side as shown. 

I found dead Amphipods on the Coot's back, between its feathers, and underneath it. It was being scavenged by ants. There was a snail in its beak when I pried it open (picture 16).

The body smelled and the eyes had shrunken. It was slimy to the touch. I flipped it over with a stick. Its foot was seemingly wounded, or at least bloody.

description:
Dead in the lagoon...

Yesterday, I received this email update from International Bird Rescue who are taking in the suffering Brown Pelicans.
"More than 250 Brown Pelicans have been admitted to Bird Rescue's California wildlife centers since May 12. Among them was a familiar face, a pelican wearing the blue band numbered Y83. He had previously recovered from fish hook injuries at Bird Rescue in January 2021. However, he was later found disoriented, walking around in a soap store last month. 
 
When wildlife ends up in places they shouldn't be, it means they need help. It's important to give them space, and call your local animal control. Y83 returned to Bird Rescue and was diagnosed with emaciation and dehydration, like the majority of the Brown Pelicans that are currently struggling across California."

https://www.birdrescue.org/bird-rescue-responds-to-major-brown-pelican-crisis-in-southern-california/

description:
Though there are dead young herons of various sizes - hatchlings to weeks-old chicks - found on the ground around the trees in the rookery at this location, the population is doing well. Fresh eggs found smashed on the ground here several times the past week; the birds are still actively laying new eggs, close to 12 weeks after roosting began here.

The active egg laying is a good indicator of the improving health of Lake Merritt. Last year, herons went through a relatively short egglaying cycle, apparently due to lack of food. Lake Merritt hadn't recovered from the drastic, devastating algal bloom disaster of late-August 2022; not enough fish in the lake to support a long egg-laying season. This year, herons are not having problems finding food at the lake.

Another sign of ongoing, active egglaying, black-crowned night herons and snowy egrets are still twig collecting and nest renovating.

description:
Overcrowding in black-crowned night heron nests is inevitable; fighting for elbow room, chicks get elbowed out of the nests. There's also some amount of co-predation going on, where birds are killing and eating other birds' young, particularly seeming to favour soft innards.

This chick was alive at the time of the observation, however despite efforts to keep it alive until the Zoo’s Heron Rescue Project could take it for transfer to rehab, the bird perished before they arrived.

The Heron Rescue Project is fostered by the Oakland Zoo's Heron Rescue Team. When you see a young heron alive and in distress on the ground in Oakland’s Downtown, Chinatown and Lake Merritt neighborhoods, you can text a photo of the bird with the location included to the Project number:
510-703-8986

Mostly staffed 9am-5pm during weekdays, however it's worthwhile sending a message no matter the time. They have staff that will collect the bird - live or dead - and if alive, transfer the bird to a rescue and rehabilitation center.

They can be contacted regarding black-crowned night herons and egrets, too.

description:
Symmetrical, intact, about 3.5 inches long, partial skeleton (breast bone) of a Cormorant found washed up on sandy  shoreline.

COMPARE 4 Cormorants. All are seabirds in the Cormorants and Shags (Phalacrocoracidae) family:

Double-crested Cormorant (Nannopterum auritum) found along Monterey Bay, CA
Brandt's (Urile penicillatus) found along Monterey Bay, CA
Pelagic Cormorant (Urile pelagicus) found along Monterey Bay, CA
Neotropic (Nannopterum brasilianum) would be a very rarely seen, vagrant along Monterey Bay

Irene's Cormorants and Shags (Phalacrocoracidae) family observations on INaturalist, worldwide: https://www.inaturalist.org/observations?taxon_id=4262&user_id=aparrot1

xxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxx

My favorite frontal head shot of Double-crested Cormorant in June: https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/166923639

Double-crested Cormorant (Nannopterum auritum) Formerly called Phalacrocorax auritus, is an aquatic diving bird in the Cormorants and Shags (Phalacrocoracidae) family. Conservation Status: Vulnerable (S3) in California. It has prominent yellow lores. Neck appears kinked in flight. Large, rounded throat pouch is yellow-orange year-round. Eyes often appear blue. Breeding adults have a wispy, white crest, a tuft of feathers curving back from behind the eyes. This dark, long-bodied diving bird floats low in the water with its neck and bill raised. It is often seen standing upright near water with wings spread out to dry. It is larger and has a shorter tail than the Neotropic Cormorant.
The Double-crested cormorant is the most widely distributed cormorant in North America, and the only one likely to be seen inland, even in the desert near bodies of water. At the coast, Double-crested Cormorants tend to nest in trees, unlike Brandt's Cormorants which nest in mud impressions on offshore rocks, and Pelagic Cormorants which nest in sides of cliffs.

Brandt's Cormorant (Urile penicillatus). Formerly called Phalacrocorax penicillatus. They are strictly Pacific Coast seabirds. They are black overall with greenish iridescence on back and pale buffy feathers at base of bill. Breeding adults have vivid cobalt-blue throat patch and blue eyes during breeding season. Immatures have a buffy breast. It dives to capture fish. It has a thicker bill and neck than similar looking Pelagic Cormorant. They are often seeing flying in long lines low over the water or standing drying their outstretched wings.

Nesting differences: Brandt's Cormorants nest in mud depressions, usually on near offshore islands and on rock pinnacles for protection. They add seaweeds to line the nests when available.
Double-crested Cormorants nest in trees.
Pelagic Cormorants nest on narrow ledges on the sides of steep coastal cliffs.

Brandt's cormorants feed, roost and nest together. A male chooses the nest site, attracts a female, then gathers seaweed for the nest while the female builds it. Both parents incubate the eggs and feed their young. Brandt's nests are nearly uniformly spatially segregated-- the length of an adult to lean over and steal the nest material of others.

Pelagic Cormorant (Urile pelagicus) Formerly called Phalacrocorax pelagicus, is an aquatic diving bird in the Cormorants and Shags (Phalacrocoracidae) family. 
It is a "small, slender cormorant with a thin, dark bill. Blackish overall with glossy green head and body and purplish neck. Breeding adults have white patches on sides of rump and limited reddish face. Strictly coastal, where it nests on cliffs. Dives to capture fish. Smaller than Brandt’s or Red-faced Cormorants, with a more slender neck and a thinner dark bill."

Ebird https://ebird.org/species/pelcor/

National Geographic Field Guide to the Birds of Western North America, ed. Jon L. Dunn, 2008, p. 88-89.

“Pelagic Cormorants are very poorly named; they are not “pelagic” at all, but are very restricted to the immediate coast. They do not forage offshore even as far as do Brandt's cormorants and Brandt's go only a couple miles out. Pelagics do not forage in flocks as is typical with Brandt’s. They rarely venture far up Elkhorn Slough.”
Monterey Birds, Don Roberson, 2nd ed. 2002, sponsored by Monterey Peninsula Audubon Society, p. 109.

Pelagic Cormorants nest on narrow ledges on the sides of steep coastal cliffs.

Neotropic Cormorant (Nannopterum brasilianum) is an aquatic diving bird in the Cormorants and Shags (Phalacrocoracidae) family. 
"Among the cormorants of North America’s Pacific Coast, the Pelagic is a small and slender species that flies with a thin, straight neck often compared to a broomstick. Breeding adults are black with glossy purple-green highlights. They have a coral-red throat patch and neat white patches on the flanks. They nest on coastal cliffs and forage in rocky water, rarely traveling far from shore despite their name. Unlike Brandt’s and Double-crested, Pelagic Cormorants are not very gregarious and are usually seen as single birds or pairs. Pelagic Cormorants are widespread along the Pacific coast and often occur with Brandt’s and Double-crested, where they are usually the least numerous of the three species. Pelagic Cormorant has a much thinner neck (straight in flight), slighter bill, narrower wings, and rather long tail."

Great Horned Owl (Bubo virginianus) Large owl in the Strigidae family that stands up to 56cm (22 inches) tall. It has prominent, widely spaced ear tufts (feathers) at sides of head. It is found in a large variety of habitats including dense woods, prairie, deserts, and in wooded towns and suburbs.

My favorite Great Horned Owl observations:
February 2024: https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/200537207
November 2023: https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/192343404

Ebird with species description, range map and sound recordings: https://ebird.org/species/grhowl/
"It is typically well-camouflaged beige and dark brown overall, but varies in color. Often engages in haunting duets, with males and females hooting back and forth. Preys upon a variety of animals, including mammals, birds and reptiles. It hunts mostly at night, sometimes at dusk. It watches from high perch, then swoops down to capture prey in its talons. It has extremely good hearing and good vision in low light conditions. Mammals make up majority of diet in most regions. It takes many rats, mice, and rabbits, also ground squirrels, opossums, and skunks. Eats some birds (especially in the north), up to size of geese, ducks, hawks, and smaller owls. Also eats snakes, lizards, frogs, insects, scorpions, but rarely fish. Feathers: Because of their nocturnal habits, Owls tend not to exhibit sexual dimorphism in their plumage. Specialized feathers and wing shape suppress the noise produced by flying, both taking off, flapping and gliding. This silent flight allows owls to hunt without being heard by their prey. Owls possess three physical attributes that are thought to contribute to their silent flight capability. First, on the leading edge of the wing, there is a comb of stiff feathers. Second, the trailing edge of the wing contains a flexible fringe. Finally, owls have downy material distributed on the tops of their wings that creates a compliant but rough surface (similar to that of a soft carpet). All these factors result in significant aerodynamic noise reduction."

Coachella Valley Preserve: For thousands of years, particles of sand from the San Bernardino Mountains and Indio Hills washed into the Coachella Valley forming a system of sand dunes. Today, these dunes are part of the Coachella Valley Preserve System, a 20,000-acre sanctuary, a desert oasis for many species of birds, reptiles, plants, and human visitors.
The Coachella Valley Preserve contains several palm oases that sit on top of San Andreas Fault lines. Underground water rises to the surface through these cracks. California Fan Palms (Washingtonia filifera) grow along the cracks where the water seeps up creating a desert oases. Many plant species thrive in the alkaline soil.
Coachella Valley sits at the convergence of four vast ecological systems - the Colorado (or Sonoran) Desert, the Mojave Desert, and the coastal and peninsular mountain ranges.

Birding Hotspot. Current access information: https://www.cnlm.org/portfolio_page/thousand-palms-oasis-preserve-coachella-valley-preserve/ (usually open Wed-Sun, street parking only)
and general information about the Preserve: https://www.blm.gov/visit/coachella-valley-preserve
